Notes: This author published some relevant outcomes from their dissertation but not all. The published data utilized was the data of participants that passed the manipulation check only, which is what we decided to include for all outcomes. The overall sample size and the descriptive statistics (means, sds) were the same for the outcomes in the dissertation and published study. The published study provided n's per cell, which we utilized for all outcomes. Since the participants were the same, we needed to keep the identifying information for the study in our dataset the same regardless of unpublished or published, in order to partition the variance correctly in the model. Since more relevant outcomes were still unpublished and came from the dissertation and this entry had the earlier date, we will use this entry. However the published data is as follows Cooke, Bazzini, Curtin & Emery (2018) https://psycnet-apa-org.libproxy.uoregon.edu/doi/10.1007/s11031-018-9671-9 and is for the outcomes state empathy and self-other overlap.

Notes: This study had two instructions that qualified as imagine-other, one focused on feelings and the other other on thoughts. They are indicated as separate by the sample_number's 1 and 2. They both are compared to the same objective condition. Comparisons to one another were not included because they were not relevant to our question. Sample 1 will include "Other" that the authors labeled as perspective taking, and sample 2 will be coded as "Other" that the authors labeled as "Empathic." Also, this study has participant's take the perspective of a target individual ( that could be in or out-group) in a dyadic interaction. Based on prior decisions, we are only using outcomes related to the target the perspective taker saw. If this was not clear, we contacted the author.
